Lab 7: Classification and Regression Trees

Ziping Xu

Classification Tree

We look at the spam email classification problem in today’s lab. The dataset is accessible at https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/spambase. There are 57 attributes with 48 continuous real [0,100] attributes of type word_freq_WORD representing percentage of words in the e-mail that match WORD and 6 continuous real [0,100] attributes of type char_freq_CHAR for percentage of characters matching CHAR. The attributes on captical words and punctuations are also included.

set.seed(1)
dat = read.csv("spambase.data", header = F)

# loading the names
names = read.table("names.txt")[, 1]
colnames(dat) = names
dat$spam = factor(dat$spam)
levels(dat$spam) = c("Non-Spam", "Spam")

# splitting training and testing set
n = dim(dat)[1]; p = 0.7
train_id = sample(seq(1, n ,1), floor(n * p))
train = dat[train_id, ]
test = dat[-train_id, ]

Let us take a simple look at the dataset. Usually in a word vector, words appearing too frequently or too rarely can be useless in predicting. We order the first 48 columns accroding to their mean frequency. On average, the words, you and your accounts for more than 2.5% of the total length. We will use tree model to comfirm whether our intuition is correct.

mean_freq = colMeans(train[, 1:48])

We further pick some varaibles to verify our intuition. We look at the most frequent word you and some ralative rarer varaibles george and report. We also select exclamation and capital run length based on our understanding of spam emails.

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(tidyr)
sel_var = c("word_freq_you", "word_freq_george", "word_freq_report", "char_freq_exclamation", "capital_run_length_average", "capital_run_length_total")
dat.explore = train[, c(sel_var, "spam")]

# Transform from wide table to long table
dat.explore.1 = gather(dat.explore, key = "Variable", value = "Value", -c("spam"))
ggplot(dat.explore.1) + geom_boxplot(aes(x = spam, y = Value)) + facet_wrap(.~Variable, scales = "free_y") + theme_minimal()

We can see that some variables have a skewed distribution, which makes the boxplot uninformative. To make the plot more meaningful, we take log for them. For the variables with most values to be 0’s (report and george), we only look at non-zero values.

dat.explore.2 = dat.explore
dat.explore.2$capital_run_length_average = log(dat.explore.2$capital_run_length_average)
dat.explore.2$capital_run_length_total = log(dat.explore.2$capital_run_length_total)
dat.explore.2$char_freq_exclamation = log(dat.explore.2$char_freq_exclamation+0.00001)
dat.explore.2$word_freq_you = log(dat.explore.2$word_freq_you+0.00001)
#dat.explore.2$word_freq_george = log(dat.explore.2$word_freq_george+0.00001)

# 

dat.explore.2$word_freq_george[dat.explore.2$word_freq_george == 0] = NA
dat.explore.2$word_freq_report[dat.explore.2$word_freq_report == 0] = NA
# dat.explore$word_freq_report = log(dat.explore$word_freq_report+0.00001)

# Transform from wide table to long table
dat.explore.2 = gather(dat.explore.2, key = "Variable", value = "Value", -c("spam"))
ggplot(dat.explore.2) + geom_boxplot(aes(x = spam, y = Value)) + facet_wrap(.~Variable, scales = "free_y") + theme_minimal()

Most of our findings verified our intuitions: 1) the commonly used words like you are useless to identify spam emails; 2) capital length and exclamation seem to be useful, which may indicate that spam emails have stronger emotions; 3) less frequent words can hardly discrimine the two labels; 4) it’s interesting to see that the word George has high frequency and seems to be predictable as George is the donor of the dataset. We may see later that hp the place he works is also selected by tree model. Using those two words may cause generalization problem when we apply the model to emails of other users.

We also find the labels are slightly unbalanced, which reminds us to adjust the output label distribution when generalize to a broader application.

table(train$spam)

    1930     1290

Fitting Tree Model

The rpart library is used to construct classification and regression trees. We use the function rpart in the package to fit the classification tree. Analogous to linear regression, we pass the formula and data. We first try splitting criterion gini: \(1-\sum_{i=1}^{2}\left(p_{i}\right)^{2}\).

library(rpart)
library(rpart.plot)  
library(rattle)
tree1 = rpart(spam ~ ., train, parms = list(split = "gini"), method = "class", cp = 0)

One of the most attractive properties of trees is that they can be graphically displayed. We use the plot() function to display the tree structure, and the text() function to display the node labels. The argument pretty=0 instructs R to include the category names for any qualitative predictors, rather than simply displaying a letter for each category.

fancyRpartPlot(tree1)

Since we didn’t penalize the size of the tree, we generated a extremely complex model. The length (or depth) of each branch is proportional to the reduction in impurity (or quality of split) of that corresponding split. There is a very long branch in our complex model. As mentioned in the lecture, we prune a tree by finding a sub-tree \(T\) that minimizes: \[ C(T)=\sum_{t=1}^{|T|} N_{t} \cdot \text{Impurity} (t)+c_{p} \cdot|T|. \] The tuning parameter \(c_p\) can be selected with cross validation. We don’t need to call external functions for cross validation as rpart will do 10 fold cross validation when cp is not specified.

When calling rpart without specifying cp, the miss-classification loss (risk) for each sub-tree is calculated by comparing the class predicted for the validation fold vs. actual class; and this risk value for each sub-tree is summed up for all folds. And the function will return a model with the lowest risk. plotcp will plot the relative cross-validation error for each sub-tree from smallest to largest.

tree.gini = rpart(spam ~ ., data = train, parms = list(split = "gini"), method = "class")
plotcp(tree.gini)

As shown in the plot, cp for 0.018 and 0.01 have the similar performances. We select the simpler model for cp = 0.018 and refit the model.

tree.gini = rpart(spam ~ ., train, parms = list(split = "gini"), method = "class", cp = 0.018)
#plot(tree.gini)
#text(tree.gini, pretty = 0)
fancyRpartPlot(tree.gini)

As we expected, you and your were not selected. The most useful symbol is exclamation symbol. The useful words are remove, hp and edu. We now look at the training and testing errors.

set.seed(2)
train.pred=predict(tree.gini, train, type="class")
table(train.pred, train$spam)

  Non-Spam     1834  231
  Spam           96 1059
sum(train.pred != train$spam) / dim(train)[1]

test.pred=predict(tree.gini, test, type="class")
table(test.pred, test$spam)

Comparing different splitting criterions

There are multiple choices of splitting measure. We have implemented Gini index. We further try information gain (or Entropy): \(-\sum_{k=1}^{K} p_{k}(m) \log p_{k}(m)\).

tree.info = rpart(spam ~ ., train, parms = list(split = "information"))
plotcp(tree.info)

train.pred=predict(tree.info, train, type="class", cp = 0.012)
table(train.pred, train$spam)
          
train.pred Non-Spam Spam
  Non-Spam     1825  199
  Spam          105 1091
sum(train.pred != train$spam) / dim(train)[1]
[1] 0.09440994
test.pred=predict(tree.info, test, type="class")
table(test.pred, test$spam)
          
test.pred  Non-Spam Spam
  Non-Spam      818   99
  Spam           40  424
sum(test.pred != test$spam) / dim(test)[1]
[1] 0.1006517

Using Entropy is slightly better than using Gini index.

Balancing labels

There are two kinds of misclassification, i.e. misclassify Spam as Non-Spam and misclassificy Non-Spam as Spam. From the confusion table in the previous section, the number of two types of errors are unbalanced.

Our model tends to make the error of predicting Spam to be Non-Spam, since in our training set Non-Spam is the dominant class. This can be a problem when we want to control certain type of errors, while in our problem the error of misclassificying Non-Spam as Spam seems more serious.

We can assign weights to adjust the unbalance to reduce the second error. In our case, since training and testing set have the same label distribution, the true testing error might increase slightly.

prop = table(train$spam) / dim(train)[1]
w = rep(1/prop[2], dim(train)[1])
w[which(train$spam == "Non-Spam")] = 1/prop[1]

tree.balance = rpart(spam ~ ., train, parms = list(split = "information"), weights = w)

train.pred=predict(tree.balance, train, type="class")
table(train.pred, train$spam)
          
train.pred Non-Spam Spam
  Non-Spam     1783  177
  Spam          147 1113
sum(train.pred != train$spam) / dim(train)[1]
[1] 0.1006211
test.pred=predict(tree.balance, test, type="class")
table(test.pred, test$spam)
          
test.pred  Non-Spam Spam
  Non-Spam      796   81
  Spam           62  442
sum(test.pred != test$spam) / dim(test)[1]
[1] 0.1035482

The mistakes of predicting Non-Spam for a real Spam sample are reduced.

Regression Tree

We will fit a regression tree on the Boston housing data. Recall that this data is located in the MASS package. In this section, our goal is to predict the variable medv from all other variables in the dataset. For the regression tree, we use the Mean Square Error (MSE) as the impurity measure to split.

library(MASS)
set.seed(1)
train = sample(1:nrow(Boston), nrow(Boston)/2) 
tree.boston=rpart(medv~.,Boston,subset=train) 
plotcp(tree.boston)

We choose cp = 0.019 as the model after pruning. In the context of a regression tree, the Entropy is is simply the sum of squared errors for the tree. We now plot the tree.

tree.boston=rpart(medv~.,Boston,subset=train, cp = 0.019) 
fancyRpartPlot(tree.boston)

The variable lstat measures the percentage of individuals with lower socioeconomic status. The tree indicates that lower values of lstat correspond to more expensive houses. The tree predicts a median house price about $21,000 for larger homes in suburbs in which residents have high socioeconomic status (rm >= 6.5 and lstat > 14). This is also the node with most samples.

We test the performance of pruned tree.

yhat=predict(tree.boston,newdata=Boston[-train,]) 
boston.test=Boston[-train,"medv"] 
plot(yhat,boston.test)
abline(0,1)

To calculate test MSE, we can do

mean((yhat-boston.test)^2)
[1] 35.16439

We see that the test MSE associated with the fitted regression tree is 35.16439.

Question: What does this MSE imply about the prediction? How do you interpret the test MSE?

The square root of the MSE (i.e. the RMSE) is around 5.93, indicating that this model leads to test predictions that are within around 5930 dollars of the true median home value for the suburb.
